<h1>Development Information</h1>

<p>This page contains various information for developers or anyone interested
in contributing to NetSurf.</p>


<h2><abbr title="Concurrent Versions System">CVS</abbr></h2>

<p>The source is kept in <abbr title="Concurrent Versions System">CVS</abbr>.
It can be accessed read-only using the following parameters:</p>

<table>
<tr><td>Protocol</td><td>pserver</td></tr>
<tr><td>Host</td><td><code>semichrome.net</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Path</td><td><code>/home/netsurf/cvs</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Module</td><td><code>netsurf</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Username</td><td><code>anonymous</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Password</td><td>(blank password)</td></tr>
</table>

<p>To check the source out using command-line CVS:</p>

<p><code>$ <strong>cvs -d :pserver:anonymous@semichrome.net:/home/netsurf/cvs
login</strong><br>
Logging in to :pserver:anonymous@semichrome.net:2401/home/netsurf/cvs<br>
CVS password: <strong>(press return)</strong><br>
$ <strong>cvs -d :pserver:anonymous@semichrome.net:/home/netsurf/cvs checkout
netsurf</strong></code></p>

<p>There is also a <a href="http://cvs.semichrome.net/netsurf/">web
interface</a> to the repository and a
<a href="http://cia.navi.cx/stats/project/NetSurf/.rss">RSS feed of
changes</a>.</p>

<p>Contact <a href="mailto:james&#64;semichrome.net">James</a> to get write
access.</p>


<h2>Compiling</h2>

<p>The recommended compiler is
<a href="http://hard-mofo.dsvr.net/gcc/">gcc</a>, either native or
cross-compiling from Linux or Unix using gccsdk.
<a href="http://netsurf.strcprstskrzkrk.co.uk/developer/">Pre-compiled ports</a>
of the libraries required are available.</p>

<p>The <a href="http://netsurf.strcprstskrzkrk.co.uk/">autobuilder</a> compiles
NetSurf every 15 minutes if changes have been checked into CVS.</p>

<p>A debug version of NetSurf can be built. This is command-line only and does
not include any of gui code, but runs natively on Linux so can be debugged and
checked using gdb, efence, valgrind, etc.</p>


<h2>Source Documentation</h2>

<p>The source is documented using <a href="http://www.doxygen.org/">Doxygen</a>
(<a href="http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/~jmb202/">RISC OS port</a>). Use
<code>doxygen Docs/Doxyfile</code> to generate the documentation from the source
tree, or <a href="http://netsurf.strcprstskrzkrk.co.uk/codedocs/">view the
latest documentation</a> generated on the autobuilder.</p>


<h2><abbr title="Internet Relay Chat">IRC</abbr></h2>

<p>The main method of communication between the developers is <abbr
title="Internet Relay Chat">IRC</abbr>. Join the <code>#netsurf-develop</code>
channel on <a href="http://www.ircnet.com/">IRCnet</a>.</p>


<h2>Translations</h2>

<p>Translations of NetSurf to other languages are welcome. No programming
knowledge is required, just the ability to use a template editor (for example
<a href="http://www.realh.co.uk/wined.html">WinEd</a>) and a text editor.</p>


